/Users/anthony/Programming/Deniable/deniable_design_doc_v2.md:34:The brand-mark *Deniable* describes the operating principle of every crew in the game (state proxies, corporate PMCs, intelligence cells, partisans — all instruments of denial). The brand is intended to outlast any single setting; future expansions can carry the *Deniable* name into other geographies and conflicts.
/Users/anthony/Programming/Deniable/deniable_design_doc_v2.md:46:By the mid-2030s, the world has settled into a tense, tripolar cold war:
/Users/anthony/Programming/Deniable/deniable_design_doc_v2.md:127:- **Aim** — prep next attack: +1 die OR remove one situational penalty
/Users/anthony/Programming/Deniable/deniable_design_doc_v2.md:162:| 1 (or lower with mods) | **Dead** — fighter removed from roster, gear is on the map (if not extracted) | — |
/Users/anthony/Programming/Deniable/deniable_design_doc_v2.md:186:In raid format, drones are **expensive expendable equipment, not crew assets.** You bring drones to a raid as part of your loadout. If shot down, they're lost. If the operator extracts with the drone, it returns to your stash.
/Users/anthony/Programming/Deniable/deniable_design_doc_v2.md:423:The hideout is **a set of data-driven UI screens, not a 3D walkable space.** Industrial-Modernist visual style, Tarkov-equivalent operational dashboard.
/Users/anthony/Programming/Deniable/deniable_design_doc_v2.md:560:- Drones become map-modifying assets — open new sightlines, drop overhead cover
/Users/anthony/Programming/Deniable/deniable_design_doc_v2.md:619:Each enemy crew faction has a doctrine tag set that flavors their AI behavior (casualty-averse, aggression, formation discipline, tech-dependence, etc.). Different factions feel different to fight against.
