### Act II → Act III transition

Similar but more dramatic:

- Bloc-level intervention may begin (one of the three blocs commits assets; new mission types appear)
- Faction relationships polarize (you're either an ally or a target of major factions)
- Some squad members may have completed personal arcs (resolved their wants/needs; they may retire from active duty)
- Climactic raid types appear (assassinate state operator, defend hideout, etc.)

### Implementation approach

World-state mutations are **scripted into anchor events**. An Act I anchor's `state_mutations` field can include:

```python
StateMutation(
    target_entity="deniable_faction_partisan",
    operation="set",
    field="properties.regional_strength",
    value="depleted_in_south_concord_aligned"
)
```

These cascading mutations make the world feel responsive to the player's actions while keeping the engine simple (just data mutations).

